Windows 11 has several editions, each tailored for different types of users and devices. Here’s a comparison of the main editions, along with their maximum CPU and RAM support:

Windows 11 Editions

1. Windows 11 Home

Target Users: General consumers and home users.

Max RAM: 128 GB

Max CPUs: Supports up to 1 CPU with 64 cores.



2. Windows 11 Pro

Target Users: Professionals and small businesses.

Max RAM: 2 TB

Max CPUs: Supports up to 1 CPU with 64 cores.

Additional Features: BitLocker, Remote Desktop, Group Policy Management.



3. Windows 11 Pro for Workstations

Target Users: Advanced users and professionals needing high performance.

Max RAM: 6 TB

Max CPUs: Supports up to 4 CPUs with 64 cores each.

Additional Features: ReFS (Resilient File System), faster file sharing.



4. Windows 11 Enterprise

Target Users: Large organizations.

Max RAM: 2 TB

Max CPUs: Supports up to 1 CPU with 64 cores.

Additional Features: Advanced security features, virtualization options, and deployment tools.



5. Windows 11 Education

Target Users: Educational institutions.

Max RAM: 2 TB

Max CPUs: Supports up to 1 CPU with 64 cores.

Additional Features: Similar to Windows 11 Enterprise but tailored for schools.



6. Windows 11 SE

Target Users: Education-focused devices (e.g., affordable laptops for students).

Max RAM: 16 GB

Max CPUs: Supports up to 1 CPU with 64 cores.

Additional Features: Simplified interface, limited to Microsoft Store apps.




Summary of Maximum Support

Max RAM:

Home: 128 GB

Pro: 2 TB

Pro for Workstations: 6 TB

Enterprise: 2 TB

Education: 2 TB

SE: 16 GB


Max CPUs:

All editions except Pro for Workstations: 1 CPU with 64 cores.

Pro for Workstations: 4 CPUs with 64 cores each.



